Researchers at Stanford University studied colour-letter pairings for 400 synesthetes born between 1970 and 1985 . 
  They found that at least six per cent learnt 'many of their matches' from the toy . 
  Synaesthesia is a neurological condition in which two senses are involuntarily joined together . 
  The researchers found that the colour of letters was most commonly associated with the magnets sold by Fisher-Price between 1971 and 1990 . 
 